## The Science of Pacing

Pacing strategy is arguably the most impactful yet underutilized aspect of competitive cycling. While most athletes focus on increasing their FTP, the difference between a good and great performance often lies in **how** power is distributed across the course.

## Key Pacing Models

### Even Pacing

The simplest strategy: maintain a constant power output throughout. Works best on flat time trials with minimal wind variation.

### Negative Split

Start conservatively, finish strong. Research shows this can yield 1-3% improvements in total time for events over 30 minutes.

### Variable Pacing (VP)

Match power to terrain. Push harder on climbs, recover on descents. This is where tools like **Power Guide** become essential.

## The Role of Data

Modern power meters and GPS units give us unprecedented access to real-time data. Combined with pre-race course analysis, athletes can:

- **Pre-plan** power targets for each segment
- **Monitor** actual vs. planned output in real-time
- **Adjust** strategy based on fatigue and conditions

## Practical Application

Using our **Power Guide** tool, you can upload any route and simulate different pacing strategies. The algorithm considers:

- Elevation profile and gradient changes
- Wind speed and direction forecasts
- Your personal power-duration curve
- Target finish time or average power

## Conclusion

The era of "just ride hard" is over. Data-driven pacing separates podium finishers from the pack. Start analyzing your races with the right tools and watch your results transform.
